{"updated": "2017-07-11T04:27:47", "news_urls": ["https://www.crunchbase.com/person/john-sandford/press"], "name": "John Sandford", "total_news_count": "1", "gender": "Male", "last_visited": "2017-06-09T09:12:00", "websites": [{"url": "http://www.facebook.com/JohnSandfordOfficial", "type": "facebook"}, {"url": "http://twitter.com/j_sandford", "type": "twitter"}], "url": "https://www.crunchbase.com/person/john-sandford", "location": "Santa Fe", "images": "https://crunchbase-production-res.cloudinary.com/image/upload/c_pad,h_140,w_140/v1413192887/p1rbqua2mfxwemnrvrzz.jpg", "news": [{"date": "May 16, 2017", "article": {"url": "http://www.startribune.com/new-york-times-bestsellers/422531274/", "publisher": "startribune.com", "uuid": "ba695b1f4fd7456a99f0e816b66d93d3", "title": "New York Times bestsellers"}, "publication": "Star Tribue", "source_url": "https://www.crunchbase.com/person/john-sandford/press"}], "_key": "087328e1dbc09d2f", "description": "John Sandford is an American novelist and former journalist. From 1971 to 1978, Camp wrote for The Miami Herald. In 1978 he moved to Minneapolis and started writing for The Saint Paul Pioneer Press as a features reporter; in 1980 he became a daily columnist. That year he was a Pulitzer finalist for a series of stories on Native American culture. In 1985, during the Midwest farm crisis, he wrote a series entitled \"Life on the Land: an American farm family\", which followed a typical southwest Minnesota farm family through the course of a full year. He worked part-time at the Pioneer Press in 1989 and left the next year. In 1989, Camp wrote two novels. The Fool\u2019s Run was published under his own name, but the publisher asked him to provide a pseudonym for Rules of Prey (Prey series) so it was published under the name \"John Sandford\". In 2007, Camp started a third series, featuring Virgil Flowers, who was a supporting character in some of the Prey novels, including Invisible Prey and Storm Prey."}
